Post Goals

  1. Provide an introduction to Z-Scores and how to use Z-score tables.

  2. Demonstrate how to calculate Z-scores.

  3. Demonstrate how to calculate the area percentange (proportion, probability).

Part 1a: Introduction to Z-Scores

  • What is a z-score: A z-score (standard score) represents the number of standard deviations a given data value "x" falls from the mean, μ.

  • How are z-scores useful?
    Z-scores are useful in statistic because it:
    • allows us to calculate the probability of a score occurring within our normal distribution.
    • enables us to compare two scores that are from different normal distributions.

  • How do z-scores work?: Z-score converts (standardizes) the scores of a normal distribution to a standard normal distribution.

  • A Z-score is calculated by subtracting the data value by the mean and dividing that by the population standard deviation (see image 1).

  • Why is this important? Z-scores are a tool statisticians use to provide a probability distribution, which allows us to calcualte the probability of a score occuring for a number of a normal distribution.

  • Z-scores also play a role in Hypothesis testing

Part 1b: Standard Normal Distribution and Z-score (Standard Score)

  • The Z-score provides the position of a given value along a standard normal distribution.

  • The position of the z-score is the number of standard deviations the data value is from the mean.

  • If the z-score is positive, it is to the right of the mean. Image 2

  • If the z-score is negative, it is to the left of the mean.

  • The area under the curve is called the area percentage.

  • The Area percentage is the proportion or probabilities between two points along the standard normal distribution

  • The area percentage for the entire curve is 1 or 100%.

  • The curve is symmetric about the mean, and the area on either size is 0.5 or 50%.

  • Z-score tables have been developed to help find the specific area under a normal curve.

  • Z-score tables come in two formats:
    1. Start from the mean and moves to the right of the standard normal distribution (aka positive z-score table).image3

    2. Start from negative infinity of the standard normal distribution and moves to the right (aka cumulative from the left table).image4

How to read the positive Z-Score Table

  • As mentioned before, the z-score table provides the area percentage under the curve. This is the probability under the curve up to the given z-score intersection (grey area of curve above table).

  • The tables are used for standard normal distributions and have values between 0 and 1.

  • The positive z-score table has values from 0.5 to 1.

  • The first column contains the number of standard deviations above the mean to one decimal place.

  • When you calculate a z-score, you first look at the first (left most column) to the first decimal place and then you look for the rest of the value by looking at the header row.

  • The header row denotes the hundredths for the z-score

  • The intersection of the row and column gives you the probability or area under the normal curve.

  • Each value in the table body is the cumulative area.

  • In the example above, if the z-score was 1.05, you would then find that the shadded area under the curve would be 0.8531.

How to read the Negative Z-Score Table

  • As mentioned before, the z-score table provides the area percentage under the curve. This is the probability under the curve up to the given z-score intersection (grey area under curve above table).

  • The tables are used for standard normal distributions and have values between 0 and 1.

  • The negative z-score table has values starting from 0 to 1.

  • The first column contains a negative number, which is the standard deviations below the mean to one decimal place.

  • When you calculate a z-score, you first look at the first (left most column) to the first decimal place and then you look for the rest of the value by looking at the header row.

  • The header row denotes the hundredths for the z-score

  • The intersection of the row and column gives you the probability or area under the normal curve.

  • Each value in the table body is the cumulative area.

  • In the example above, if the z-score was -1.32, you would then find that the shadded area under the curve would be 0.0934 (9.34%).
